# 18. Final Outcome

## 18.1 Final Description
Describe the final version of your project.

**Response:**  
`Lazy Pinball is a hand-built tabletop pinball machine powered by an ESP32 microcontroller. Players use two physical roller lever switches to control two servo-driven flipper arms at the bottom of an inclined MDF playfield. The ball is launched from the top, rolls down the slope, and players attempt to keep it in play using the flippers. The outer structure is laser cut MDF and the interior is cardboard. The system runs on MicroPython with no app or screen. The entire experience is physical and immediate.`

## 18.2 What Works Well
- Flipper response is fast and satisfying â€” the snap of the servo feels close to a real pinball machine
- The roller lever switches are comfortable and quick to press repeatedly
- The laser cut MDF enclosure looks clean and holds together solidly

## 18.3 What Still Needs Improvement
- Ball speed and slope angle could be better calibrated for a more balanced difficulty
- Flipper arm attachment to servo horn could be more secure under heavy repeated use
- No scoring system â€” a future version could add an LED counter or buzzer feedback

## 18.4 What Changed From the Original Plan
How did the project change from the initial idea?

**Response:**  
`The core concept stayed consistent throughout â€” two flippers, two buttons, one ball. The main changes were in execution. The wiring approach had to be revised after button signal issues, and the internal layout was adjusted several times before the electronics fit cleanly inside the enclosure. Scoring was considered as a stretch feature but was cut to keep the build focused and finishable within the four weeks.`

