# 19. Reflection

## 19.1 Team Reflection
What did your team do well?  
What slowed you down?  
How well did you manage time, tasks, and responsibilities?

**Response:**  
`The project was driven primarily by one team member on the technical side â€” concept development, electronics, coding, wiring logic, and system decisions â€” while the other focused on physical fabrication including laser cutting, cardboard construction, and internal layout. The division worked reasonably well in terms of getting things done, but integration took longer than expected because the two workstreams weren't always in sync. Time management was tight in week 3 when the physical and electronic builds had to come together at the same time.`

## 19.2 Technical Reflection
What did you learn about:
- electronics,
- coding,
- mechanisms,
- fabrication,
- integration?

**Response:**  
`We learned that servo motors require a separate power supply and a shared ground â€” something that caused significant debugging time early on. Button wiring with PULL_UP logic was unintuitive at first but made sense once we understood how the signal works. On the code side, edge detection for button presses (only triggering on the transition from unpressed to pressed) was a key insight that made the interaction feel correct. Integration â€” getting physical components and electronics to work together inside a fixed enclosure â€” was harder than either part alone.`

## 19.3 Design Reflection
What did you learn about: 
- designing for play,
- delight,
- clarity,
- physical interaction,
- player understanding,
- iteration?

**Response:**  
`The biggest design lesson was that physical feedback matters enormously. The lever switch feels better to press than a tactile button would have, and that small choice changes how the whole experience feels. We also learned that simplicity works â€” the game is just press, flip, react, and that's enough to make people want another turn. Clarity came from the physical layout itself: two buttons, two flippers, one ball. No explanation needed. Iteration on the slope angle and flipper position taught us that small physical changes have a big effect on gameplay feel.`

## 19.4 If You Had One More Week
What would you improve next?

**Response:**  
`We would add a scoring system â€” either a buzzer that reacts when the ball passes a sensor, or an LED counter that tracks how long the ball stays in play. We would also refine the flipper arm shape and attachment to handle faster, heavier balls more reliably, and experiment with adding bumpers on the playfield surface to make the ball's path less predictable and more exciting`

